Crate root for `ctx-scan`, a standalone tool that walks an arbitrary directory (not necessarily a git repo) and maintains a `.context/` mirror of per-file/per-dir summaries. This file is pure module wiring plus the crate-level doc comment; no logic lives here.

Key architectural facts stated only in this doc comment (easy to miss since they're not in any single submodule): prompt files are read at runtime from a configurable directory (default `prompts/`, relative to process cwd) — deliberately decoupled from the tree being scanned, so prompts aren't versioned alongside the target repo. Change detection is entirely content-hash based via `hash`, meaning `--check` never invokes a model; `--update` regenerates only files whose hash changed and also prunes orphaned mirror artifacts via `reconcile`; `--prune` runs that same orphan-pruning logic alone, also with no model call.

Programmatic entry points are `runner::scan_run`, `runner::check_run`, `runner::update_run`, `runner::prune_run`. CLI entry point is `cli::dispatch`. Module list: `contract` (shared types/traits between modules), `error`, `hash`, `readme`, `reconcile`, `render` (private — internal to runner's output formatting), `staleness`, `walker`. Anyone adding a new CLI mode should wire it through both `cli` and a corresponding `runner::*_run` function to keep the two entry points in sync.